Note:
PowerPC 64-bit Linux System Call Interface

This file implements Linux PowerPC 64-bit system calls for the Runa compiler.

Platform-specific details:
- Platform: Linux PowerPC 64-bit (ppc64le)
- Syscall mechanism: sc instruction
- Syscall number register: r0
- Argument registers: r3-r8 (up to 6 arguments)
- Return value: r3
- Error indication: r3 contains errno (negative on error)

Linux PowerPC 64-bit syscall convention:
- r0 = syscall number
- r3-r8 = arguments 1-6
- Stack = arguments 7+ (if needed)
- sc instruction triggers kernel
- r3 = return value (or errno if negative)

PowerPC 64-bit syscall numbers differ from other architectures.
This file provides both syscall number constants and wrapper functions.

Dependencies: None (uses inline assembly for syscalls)
:End Note

Note:
============================================================================
SYSCALL NUMBER CONSTANTS
============================================================================
Linux PowerPC 64-bit syscall numbers
:End Note

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes 27 SYS_* nullary accessor
procs returning the platform's syscall number for each named operation.
Linux PowerPC's table is sourced from the kernel header
`arch/powerpc/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h` (canonical for both ppc64le and
ppc32). Two accessors that the dispatcher requires are SYS_EXIT (thread
exit) and SYS_EXIT_GROUP (whole-process exit); these match the kernel's
__NR_exit and __NR_exit_group values on PowerPC.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each SYS_* accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer
value. The dispatcher's `SYS_EXIT from Syscall` and
`SYS_EXIT_GROUP from Syscall` lookups resolve to these procs on PowerPC
targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1. Wave 2 will rename
to `powerpc_SYS_EXIT` / `powerpc_SYS_EXIT_GROUP`; Wave 1 keeps the bare
form to match the still-bare dispatcher. The numeric values are platform
header constants, not invention: SYS_EXIT=1 and SYS_EXIT_GROUP=234 per
the Linux PowerPC kernel unistd table.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary, and the
inlined integer literal becomes an immediate operand to the subsequent
`syscall_N` invocation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning an exit-syscall number carries no security state. Callers who
pass the returned value to `syscall_1` invoke a syscall that terminates
the calling thread (SYS_EXIT) or the entire process group (SYS_EXIT_GROUP).
After termination the caller's address space and all open file
descriptors are released by the kernel; any sensitive in-memory data
that has not been explicitly zeroed before the syscall is reclaimable
from freed physical pages until the kernel zeroes them on next
allocation. Security-sensitive callers MUST explicitly wipe memory
(e.g. via `mlock` + memset) before invoking exit if leak-prevention is
required.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_SYS_EXIT" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "powerpc_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 234
End Process

