Note:
============================================================================
GENERIC SYSCALL WRAPPERS
============================================================================
PowerPC 64-bit syscall wrappers with inline assembly
These invoke the kernel using PowerPC 64-bit syscall mechanism (sc instruction)
:End Note

Process called "powerpc_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 0 arguments
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -16(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 1 argument
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = arg1, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Load argument 1 into r3
        ld r3, -16(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -24(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 2 arguments
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = arg1, r4 = arg2, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Load argument 1 into r3
        ld r3, -16(sp)
        
        # Load argument 2 into r4
        ld r4, -24(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -32(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 3 arguments
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = arg1, r4 = arg2, r5 = arg3, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Load argument 1 into r3
        ld r3, -16(sp)
        
        # Load argument 2 into r4
        ld r4, -24(sp)
        
        # Load argument 3 into r5
        ld r5, -32(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -40(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 4 arguments
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = arg1, r4 = arg2, r5 = arg3, r6 = arg4, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Load argument 1 into r3
        ld r3, -16(sp)
        
        # Load argument 2 into r4
        ld r4, -24(sp)
        
        # Load argument 3 into r5
        ld r5, -32(sp)
        
        # Load argument 4 into r6
        ld r6, -40(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -48(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 5 arguments
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = arg1, r4 = arg2, r5 = arg3, r6 = arg4, r7 = arg5, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Load argument 1 into r3
        ld r3, -16(sp)
        
        # Load argument 2 into r4
        ld r4, -24(sp)
        
        # Load argument 3 into r5
        ld r5, -32(sp)
        
        # Load argument 4 into r6
        ld r6, -40(sp)
        
        # Load argument 5 into r7
        ld r7, -48(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -56(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_6" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    PowerPC 64-bit syscall with 6 arguments
    r0 = syscall number, r3 = arg1, r4 = arg2, r5 = arg3, r6 = arg4, r7 = arg5, r8 = arg6, r3 = return value, sc instruction
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into r0
        ld r0, -8(sp)
        
        # Load argument 1 into r3
        ld r3, -16(sp)
        
        # Load argument 2 into r4
        ld r4, -24(sp)
        
        # Load argument 3 into r5
        ld r5, -32(sp)
        
        # Load argument 4 into r6
        ld r6, -40(sp)
        
        # Load argument 5 into r7
        ld r7, -48(sp)
        
        # Load argument 6 into r8
        ld r8, -56(sp)
        
        # Invoke kernel
        sc
        
        # Store result from r3
        std r3, -64(sp)
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
HIGH-LEVEL SYSCALL WRAPPERS
============================================================================
These provide convenient named functions for common syscalls
:End Note

Process called "powerpc_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_READ()
    Return powerpc_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_WRITE()
    Return powerpc_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open a file
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_OPEN()
    Return powerpc_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close a file descriptor
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return powerpc_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Exit process immediately
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_EXIT()
    Return powerpc_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Adjust program break (heap boundary)
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_BRK()
    Return powerpc_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map memory region
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_MMAP()
    Return powerpc_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory region
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return powerpc_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

@Reasoning
The cross-platform syscall dispatcher exposes two additional high-level
wrappers that complete the file-I/O surface required by Runa stdlib
callers on every platform: `syscall_fstat` (retrieve file metadata by
descriptor) and `syscall_lseek` (reposition the file offset). On Linux
PowerPC these route through SYS_FSTAT (108) and SYS_LSEEK (19)
respectively per the kernel's
`arch/powerpc/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h` table.

These complete the 10 dispatcher-required `syscall_<name>` bare-form
wrappers (read, write, open, close, exit, brk, mmap, munmap, fstat,
lseek) that every platform module must export so the dispatcher's
bare-name routing resolves uniformly across platforms.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
`syscall_fstat` forwards (fd, statbuf) to `syscall_2` with SYS_FSTAT(108)
as the syscall number. On PowerPC the `struct stat` layout follows the
kernel's `stat64` definition on 32-bit PowerPC and the native `stat` on
64-bit PowerPC; callers must allocate the correct buffer size for their
target ABI. `syscall_lseek` forwards (fd, offset, whence) to `syscall_3`
with SYS_LSEEK(19). PowerPC's lseek entry handles full 64-bit offsets on
ppc64; on ppc32 use SYS__LLSEEK (140) for offsets exceeding 2^31-1.

Both wrappers issue the `sc` instruction via the generic dispatcher,
load R0 with the syscall number and R3-R8 with arguments, then return
the kernel-supplied value (positive=result, negative=errno) in R3.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper adds a single Runa-level Let + Return on top of the
generic `syscall_N` body. The kernel-mode trap (`sc` instruction) and
register switch dominate the total cost; the wrapper indirection is
negligible (2-3 host instructions). For hot-path lseek (e.g. random-
access I/O loops), prefer calling `syscall_3` directly with the literal
SYS_LSEEK constant inlined; the wrapper exists for dispatcher contract
compliance rather than as a recommended fast path. Avoid caching or
memoising results; both syscalls have side effects (lseek mutates the
fd offset; fstat reads kernel-tracked metadata that may change between
calls).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
File-descriptor and pointer arguments pass verbatim to the kernel.
The wrapper performs no validation; the kernel enforces all access
controls (DAC, capabilities, mount namespace, LSM policy, seccomp
filters). Callers MUST NOT invoke these on untrusted fd values without
prior validation.

For `syscall_fstat`: the statbuf must point to writable caller memory
of sufficient size for the target ABI's stat structure; insufficient
buffer space causes the kernel to corrupt adjacent memory if the
caller provides a too-small buffer (the syscall itself does not
length-check). For `syscall_lseek`: untrusted offset+whence
combinations can yield arbitrary file positions; the kernel will
reject offsets outside the file's valid range with EINVAL on
conforming Linux versions, but pre-EINVAL kernels (pre-2.6) may
silently truncate. Caller MUST check the sign of the return value
before treating the value as a position result.

Errno propagation: kernel returns -errno in R3 for failure. The
wrapper returns this verbatim; positive values are valid syscall
results.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by fd; routes through SYS_FSTAT (108) on PowerPC Linux
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return powerpc_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Reposition file offset; routes through SYS_LSEEK (19) on PowerPC Linux
    For 64-bit offsets on ppc32 use SYS__LLSEEK (140); ppc64 handles full 64-bit here
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return powerpc_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on Linux PowerPC.
    __NR_ioctl is 54 (Linux PowerPC arch/powerpc/include/uapi/asm/
    unistd.h, shared by ppc32 and ppc64 because both architectures
    keep an identical low-numbered Linux syscall table). Three-arg
    shape (fd, request, argp). PowerPC calling convention uses r3-r5
    for arguments and r0 for the syscall number, with sc as the
    syscall instruction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling powerpc_SYS_IOCTL() (returns 54)
    and powerpc_syscall_3(54, fd, cmd, arg). The PowerPC sc
    convention loads 54 into r0, fd into r3, cmd into r4, arg into
    r5, then issues sc; r3 holds the result on return (with CR0.SO
    set on error per the PowerPC Linux ABI — decoded inside
    syscall_3 to negative-errno).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in the kernel — one FD-table lookup and a driver
    vtable jump. The PowerPC sc transition is comparable to x86
    syscall in cost. Terminal-related ioctls (TCGETS, TIOCGWINSZ)
    are cheap memcpy-from-tty operations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The kernel validates fd against the FD table and dispatches cmd
    through file_operations.unlocked_ioctl. arg, if a pointer, is
    dereferenced by the kernel with the structure size implied by
    cmd; callers must size the buffer to match. The CR0.SO error
    flag is decoded inside powerpc_syscall_3, so the integer
    returned here is in the canonical "negative-errno on failure"
    form.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let syscall_num be powerpc_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return powerpc_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
SYSCALL CONSTANTS
============================================================================
PowerPC 64-bit platform-specific constants (file flags, permissions, etc.)
:End Note

@Reasoning
The dispatcher exposes six file-open flag constants (O_RDONLY, O_WRONLY,
O_RDWR, O_CREAT, O_TRUNC, O_APPEND) that callers pass to `syscall_open`
to control file access mode and creation semantics. On Linux PowerPC
these follow the Linux generic numeric values (the same on every Linux
architecture per `include/uapi/asm-generic/fcntl.h`): O_RDONLY=0,
O_WRONLY=1, O_RDWR=2, O_CREAT=64 (0o100), O_TRUNC=512 (0o1000),
O_APPEND=1024 (0o2000).

PowerPC does NOT use the Darwin/BSD style numbering (0x200/0x400/0x8);
the Linux ABI on PowerPC inherits the asm-generic table.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The dispatcher's `O_CREAT from Syscall` etc. lookups resolve to these
procs on PowerPC targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1.
Bodies are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.

Values match the Linux kernel header `include/uapi/asm-generic/fcntl.h`
which PowerPC includes verbatim.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
The integer literal becomes an immediate operand in the subsequent
bitwise-OR that callers typically perform to compose open flags (e.g.
`O_RDWR | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC`).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file-open flag constant carries no security state. The
SECURITY implications belong to the caller's flag composition:
- O_CREAT without O_EXCL races with attacker-controlled symlinks in
  predictable paths (TOCTOU); sandboxed callers should use openat with
  O_NOFOLLOW.
- O_TRUNC on attacker-influenced paths can destroy data; validate
  paths against an allowlist before composing.
- O_APPEND does not guarantee atomicity of multi-write append on
  network filesystems; security-sensitive log writers should use
  O_APPEND in combination with explicit fsync after each record.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_O_RDONLY" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "powerpc_O_WRONLY" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "powerpc_O_RDWR" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "powerpc_O_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return 64  Note: 0o100; create file if it does not exist
End Process

Process called "powerpc_O_TRUNC" returns Integer:
    Return 512  Note: 0o1000; truncate file to zero length on open
End Process

Process called "powerpc_O_APPEND" returns Integer:
    Return 1024  Note: 0o2000; writes append to end-of-file atomically
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
File permission constants for use as the `mode` argument to `creat(2)`,
`open(2)` with O_CREAT, `mkdir(2)`, and `chmod(2)`. POSIX-style octal
permission bits combine three triples (owner/group/world, each
read/write/execute) into a single integer. The dispatcher requires
two standard mode constants: MODE_0644 (owner read+write, group+world
read; standard for non-executable files) and MODE_0755 (owner full
access, group+world read+execute; standard for binaries and
directories).

These values are POSIX-defined and identical across every Linux
architecture; PowerPC inherits the generic numbering: 0o644 = 420
decimal, 0o755 = 493 decimal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value
in decimal form (the kernel accepts any integer encoding; we use
decimal for clarity in the Runa source while documenting the octal
representation in a Note: comment).

The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to these
procs on PowerPC targets via the bare-name route established in
Wave 1. Wave 2 will rename to `powerpc_MODE_0644` /
`powerpc_MODE_0755` once the dispatcher migrates to the prefix pattern.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Do not introduce computation here; the values are header-defined and
must not be derived from runtime state.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument to file-creating
syscalls are responsible for ensuring the requested permission
matches the intended access policy.

Common pitfalls:
- 0644 makes a file world-readable; do not use for files containing
  secrets (private keys, credentials, session tokens).
- 0755 makes a binary world-executable; combined with a setuid bit
  this becomes a privilege-escalation vector if the executable can
  be modified by an attacker.

The kernel applies the process umask to the requested mode before
storing on disk; callers needing the exact requested mode must
`umask(0)` before the create call (and restore the umask after).
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0o644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "powerpc_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0o755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
MEMORY PROTECTION FLAGS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
Memory protection flags for `mmap(2)` and `mprotect(2)`'s `prot`
argument, controlling whether pages can be read, written, executed, or
none of those. The dispatcher exposes four PROT_* accessors which
callers typically bitwise-OR to compose a protection mask (e.g.
`PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE` for a writable data page).

Values are Linux-generic (`include/uapi/asm-generic/mman-common.h`):
PROT_NONE=0, PROT_READ=1, PROT_WRITE=2, PROT_EXEC=4. PowerPC inherits
these without modification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer
value. The dispatcher's `PROT_READ from Syscall` etc. lookups resolve
to these procs on PowerPC targets via the bare-name route established
in Wave 1. Bodies are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.

Callers compose flags via bitwise OR; the kernel rejects combinations
that violate per-architecture rules (e.g. PowerPC enforces W^X on
ppc64le with `noexec` mount options, returning -EACCES on combined
PROT_WRITE|PROT_EXEC for filesystem-backed pages).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
The composed protection mask becomes an immediate operand to the
subsequent `syscall_mmap` or `mprotect` invocation, eliminating any
runtime indirection.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a memory-protection constant carries no security state. The
SECURITY implications belong to the caller's mask composition:

- PROT_WRITE | PROT_EXEC simultaneously (W^X violation) enables code
  injection attacks; callers should request PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE,
  populate the memory, then mprotect-up to PROT_READ|PROT_EXEC. JITs
  and dynamic loaders that need the combined mapping should use
  separate write-only and execute-only mappings of the same physical
  memory.
- PROT_NONE pages (guard pages) trap on any access; useful for stack
  overflow detection and isolating memory regions, but accidentally
  mapping a needed region as PROT_NONE causes SIGSEGV.
- PROT_EXEC without PROT_READ is supported on PowerPC but uncommon;
  some kernel hardening modules (CONFIG_HARDENED_USERCOPY) may
  restrict execute-only mappings.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_PROT_NONE" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: No access permitted
End Process

Process called "powerpc_PROT_READ" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Pages can be read
End Process

Process called "powerpc_PROT_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Pages can be written
End Process

Process called "powerpc_PROT_EXEC" returns Integer:
    Return 4  Note: Pages can be executed
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
MEMORY MAPPING FLAGS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
Memory mapping flags for `mmap(2)`'s `flags` argument, controlling the
sharing model, address-fixing behaviour, and anonymous-vs-file-backed
mapping selection. The dispatcher exposes four MAP_* accessors:
MAP_SHARED (changes visible to other mappings of same region),
MAP_PRIVATE (copy-on-write; changes invisible to other mappings),
MAP_FIXED (kernel must honour the supplied address or fail), and
MAP_ANONYMOUS (mapping is not backed by any file, contents zero-filled).

Values are Linux-generic per `include/uapi/asm-generic/mman.h`:
MAP_SHARED=1, MAP_PRIVATE=2, MAP_FIXED=16, MAP_ANONYMOUS=32. PowerPC
inherits these without modification.

NOTE: PowerPC's MAP_ANONYMOUS value (32) differs from BSD/Darwin
(0x1000). Cross-platform code MUST use the dispatcher-routed
`MAP_ANONYMOUS from Syscall` rather than a hard-coded literal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer
value. Callers compose flags via bitwise OR (e.g. anonymous private
mapping for heap allocation: `MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_ANONYMOUS = 34`).
The dispatcher routes `MAP_SHARED from Syscall` etc. to these procs
on PowerPC targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1.

The kernel rejects invalid combinations:
- MAP_SHARED and MAP_PRIVATE are mutually exclusive (-EINVAL if both
  set; one MUST be set).
- MAP_FIXED requires the supplied addr to be page-aligned (-EINVAL
  if not).
- MAP_ANONYMOUS implies fd=-1 and offset=0; otherwise some Linux
  versions return -EINVAL.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
The composed flag mask becomes an immediate operand to the subsequent
`syscall_mmap` invocation.

PowerPC-specific note: large-page mappings (huge pages) require
MAP_HUGETLB (0x40000) which is NOT in the dispatcher's surface;
callers needing huge pages must use a literal or define their own
constant. The four dispatched flags cover the standard mmap use cases
on PowerPC.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a memory-mapping constant carries no security state. The
SECURITY implications belong to the caller's flag composition:

- MAP_SHARED on a file the caller can read but not write allows other
  processes that share the mapping to observe the caller's reads
  (timing side channel for cache attacks).
- MAP_FIXED unconditionally replaces any existing mapping at the
  requested address, including kernel-internal mappings (vDSO, vsyscall
  page) on some kernels. Use MAP_FIXED_NOREPLACE (0x100000, not in
  this surface) when you need MAP_FIXED's address-honouring behaviour
  without the silent-replacement risk.
- MAP_ANONYMOUS pages are zero-filled by the kernel before user
  access; no stale data leakage from previous owners. This is a
  hard kernel guarantee on PowerPC and all Linux architectures.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_MAP_SHARED" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Share changes with other mappings
End Process

Process called "powerpc_MAP_PRIVATE" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Changes are private (copy-on-write)
End Process

Process called "powerpc_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 16  Note: Interpret addr exactly; do not relocate
End Process

Process called "powerpc_MAP_ANONYMOUS" returns Integer:
    Return 32  Note: Anonymous memory; not file-backed; zero-filled
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2)
measures relative to end-of-file. Linux PowerPC inherits the same
values as every Linux architecture, defined in `include/uapi/linux/fs.h`
and the POSIX specification. These match the bare-name dispatcher's
expectations and the `syscall_lseek` wrapper's `whence` parameter.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` to this proc on PowerPC
targets via the bare-name pattern still in force during Wave 1.
Bodies are non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its
own. Callers that pass user-influenced `offset` values into `lseek`
with these whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file
position against the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled
negative offset combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected
position prior to file start, which `lseek` will reject with EINVAL
on conforming Linux kernels.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "powerpc_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Seek from beginning of file
End Process

Process called "powerpc_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Seek from current position
End Process

Process called "powerpc_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Seek from end of file
End Process

Process called "powerpc_STDIN_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "powerpc_STDOUT_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "powerpc_STDERR_FILENO" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process
